        <div class="code-container">
            <button class="copy-button" onclick="copyCode(this)">Copy Code</button>
            <pre><code class="language-cpp">class Solution {
public:
    // Given an array nums, return true if it could be a rotation of a
    // non-decreasing sorted array. Duplicates are allowed.
    //
    // Key insight:
    //   A valid rotated sorted array has AT MOST ONE "drop" —
    //   a position i where nums[i] &gt; nums[(i+1) % n].
    //
    //   Why at most one?
    //   - A sorted (non-decreasing) array has 0 drops.
    //   - Rotating it shifts the single wrap-around point to some
    //     interior position, creating exactly 1 drop.
    //   - If there are 2 or more drops, the array cannot be a rotation
    //     of any sorted sequence.
    //
    // We compare each element with its CIRCULAR next neighbour
    // (using modulo) and count how many drops occur.
    // If drops &lt;= 1 → valid rotation, return true.
    // If drops &gt;= 2 → impossible, return false.
    //
    // Examples:
    //   [3,4,5,1,2]  drops at index 2 (5&gt;1)            → 1 drop  → true
    //   [2,1,3,4]    drops at index 0 (2&gt;1) and 3 (4&gt;2)→ 2 drops → false
    //   [1,2,3]      no drops                            → 0 drops → true
    //   [1,1,1]      no drops                            → 0 drops → true
    //
    // Time : O(n)    Space: O(1)

    bool check(vector&lt;int&gt;&amp; nums) {
        int n = nums.size();
        int drops = 0;

        for (int i = 0; i &lt; n; i++) {
            // Compare current element with the next one (circularly)
            if (nums[i] &gt; nums[(i + 1) % n]) {
                drops++;
            }
            // More than one drop → cannot be a rotated sorted array
            if (drops &gt; 1) return false;
        }

        return true;
    }
};</code></pre>
        </div>
